{
  "doc_id": "15501",
  "text": "Radiotherapy induces DNA damage by multiple mechanisms including base damage and single-and double-strand DNA breaks; damage that is dependent on PARP activity for its repair. Numerous in vitro and in vivo studies using different classes of PARP inhibitors have reported enhancement of the cytotoxicity of radiation in a number of tumour types, including colorectal cancers [CITATION_1] and gliomas [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] ). More recently, work by Anthony Chalmers' group has shown that this radio-potentiation is enhanced in rapidly proliferating cells and cells defective in DNA DSB repair compared with normal tissue [CITATION_4] . These data support a role for combining radiotherapy and PARP inhibitors in patients with cancer, and clinical trials are finally underway (www.clinicaltrials.gov) with results eagerly awaited.",
